name: 1950s ivory strapless dress (was £265)
description:
This is a very beautiful dress from the late 1950s possibly early 60s.

It is made from what I believe is an acetate satin, which is quite heavy in texture.

It has a boned corset bodice, full gathered skirt with sewn-in net petticoat.

There are stunning glass pearls decorating the top of the front and back of the bodice which become smaller towards the waist, with a sweetheart neckline that is very elegant!

It is what they call 'Ballerina' length, which just skims mid-shin on me. The skirt has a lot of movement but is not too full. 
The length is perfect for dancing and no need to worry about getting mud on your dress if you have a 'British summer' wedding!

It has an early nylon zip at the back with hook and eyes, and popper fastening to make it a little more secure. Straps or a halter neck could easily be added if concerned about it slipping. 
On me it stayed up perfectly.

Condition is good, the only fault seems to be in certain lights it is whiter in places within the folds of the skirt where it has aged, it is hardly noticeable, but best seen in photo no.3

It looks to be home made due to some hand stitching around the zip and pearls.

All in all, a very cute and flattering dress that is perfect for a party/ball or wedding!

Measures:

Bust - 32 to 34 ins 
Waist - 25.5 
Height of bodice - 8 to 9.5 ins 
Length of skirt - 29 ins 
Total length from top of bodice - 38.5 ins

name: Edwardian cotton lawn dress (was £195)
description:
If you lusted after the clothes in 'A Room With A View' then this is the dress for you!

A beautifully embroidered pure white crisp cotton dress from the 1900s.

It has a panel of Broidery Anglais down the centre and fine white-work on the bodice.

Tiny pin tucks and pleats all around the dress.

There are large poppers fastening the back which must be a later addition, possibly 1950s, and hook and eye catches. 
The waist band has ties so it can be left a little lose.

It is an XSmall size as it is a little tight on me {I am UK size 6/8} around the waist/arm pits and neck, but if you are a petite lady then this will look stunning! 
Alternatively, due to its simple construction, these tight areas could be adjusted by a seamstress for a better fit.

Condition is good for its 100 years, there are darned areas under the arms, and a patch that looks very old {see photo 5}. A small rust spot at the back of the collar. It is very clean, with no stains.
